 Julian Murphet present a comprehensive set of new research on the relationship between sound and writing over time from a range of eminent, established and emerging sound studies scholars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aAvery, Tamlyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerland, Jody, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooks, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBull, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByron, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCamlot, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClair, Justin St., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenney, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllison, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFree, Imogen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrimshaw-Aagaard, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGroth, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGroth, Helen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHalliday, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, K. C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLorange, Astrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorrissette, Noelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphet, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphet, Julian, e